is throws a TypeError. Because `processUser` silently swallows errors (finding 2), this TypeError results in `handleRequest` returning `null` with no indication of the fault. The parameter type is also implicit `any`, removing all static protection.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     function validate(data) {\n       const name = data.name.trim();\n       return { ok: true, name };\n     }\n     ```\n\n4. **Braceless single-statement if — CLAUDE.md violation**\n   - File: `review-src/handler.ts:21`\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - Description: The guard dispatching to `processAdmin` uses a braceless one-liner. The project's CLAUDE.md requires braces on every control-flow body: \"Never write braceless one-liners. Every `if`, `else`, `else if`, `for`, `while`, and each `case`/`default` body in a `switch` must use `{ }` blocks.\" This is a direct rule violation, not a preference.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     if (payload.admin === true) return processAdmin(payload);\n     ```\n\n5. **Missing types on handleRequest — implicit any at the module boundary**\n   - File: `review-src/handler.ts:13`\n   - Severity (initial): Important\n   - Description: `handleRequest(req)` has no parameter type annotation and no return type. `req` is implicit `any`, which means TypeScript cannot catch callers passing the wrong shape. The existing `RawRequest` interface is declared in the same file and is the correct type for this parameter. A missing return type also means the compiler cannot verify callers handle the return value correctly.\n   - Code context:\n     ```typescript\n     export function handleRequest(req) {\n     ```\n\n## Project Guidelines\n\nFrom CLAUDE.md:\n- \"Always use braces for control flow bodies: Never write braceless one-liners.\"\n\n## Request\n\nValidate these 5 findings: confirm or reject each, revise my initial severity assignments where needed, and identify any cross-cutting patterns across the findings.\n","uuid":"5567dd57-